                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I let this go before but having just watched Return of the King on DVD, it started to bother me again.  <img src="images/smiles/eusa_eh.gif" alt="eusa_eh.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
SPOILERS*** SPOILERS***SPOLIERS***
<br />
BELOW
<br />

<br />
First I’ll let you know I have not read the LOTR books, that I am guilty of. However, we all know that Hollywood has a way of writing their own chapters when making a movie based on a book. I don’t know if this is the case with ROTK or not. I am also a Gandalf fan, he is my favorite.
<br />

<br />
When Gandalf learns of the threat to the city of Minas Tirith, he rides for Gondor and the white city. Jump ahead a bit in the movie… it’s nighttime Gandalf is smoking a pipe, pippin looking at his newly acquired armor and they have a conversation.
<br />

<br />
Pippin: We've got the white wizard. That's got to count for something.
<br />

<br />
Gandalf speaks of the Witch King with a tone of terror in his voice. As if he were scared or knew he would have to battle him. He says he is Sauron's Deadliest Servant the one they say no LIVING man can kill.
<br />

<br />
This is where my problem begins; from this point forward tension builds to what I think should have been a great battle between gandalf and the Witch King.
<br />

<br />
Evidence below.
<br />

<br />
Witch King: Send forth all legions. Do not stop the attack until the city is taken. Slay them all. 
<br />
Gothmog: What of the wizard? 
<br />
Witch King: I will break him.
<br />

<br />
Sounds like building pressure to me…
<br />

<br />
Witch King: You fool. No man can kill me. Die now.  ( he doesn’t say living like gandalf just “ No man “ but remember I’m a gandalf fan  <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />  he he he )
<br />
Eowyn: I am no man.
<br />

<br />
My problem is NOT that a woman killed the Witch King. I would feel the same if any other character had done the deed. Man, Woman, hobbit or dwarf it would not matter.
<br />

<br />
What happened to Gandalf in the Two Towers? He transitioned from Gandalf the Grey to Gandalf the white. What caused this transition? DEATH
<br />

<br />
Gandalf: Gandalf? Yes... that was what they used to call me. Gandalf the Gray. That was my name. 
<br />
Gimli: Gandalf... 
<br />
Gandalf: *I* am Gandalf the White. And I come back to you now - at the turn of the tide.
<br />

<br />
A Gandalf fan could argue ( and I will  <img src="images/smiles/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="icon_biggrin.gif" border="0" />  ) that he had died so there for he was not technically “ Living “ or at least that he had died, so he could kill the Witch King.
<br />

<br />
I just think it would have flowed better with the story and why build the pressure between Gandalf and The Witch King if there was to be no fight ? I understand the Witch King kills her father and all, but two of the movie's most powerful characters going head to head would have been awesome… maybe it will be on the extended version…
<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_pray.gif" alt="eusa_pray.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: darkred">Isevan Hypnos</span></span>
<br />
<span style="color: darkblue">Enchanter of the 52nd Era</span>
<br />
<span style="color: blue">Saryn</span>
<br />

<br />
