                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Interesting point, and I think Tolkien would agree with you in terms of Gandalf dying. Tolkien was a very devoted Roman Catholic and his faith deeply influenced his writings as well as those of his close friend, C.S. Lewis. Also Tolkien said he didn't intend the Lord of the Rings to be allagorical to the Revelations story, he certainly drew heavily on the tapistry of the story. 
<br />

<br />
Gandalf in this light comes to focus as the Christ figure in the story, going to death the Grey, wearing a sullied cloth, only to rise White. I think it's a strong agrument, and I'll leave it to you to figure out how angels, Mary, and other compelling features of Roman Catholic beliefs are woven into the story. I think of course his clear stance that it wasn't to be taken as literal, leave the idea for anyone slaying Witch King (his counterpart is in the book of Revelation) really open, as I'm sure Revelation isn't scripted with a woman kill him in the end. 
<br />

<br />
That being said, I see why you are hesitent to accept that part of the tale, I found it equally - off. Wizard battles are really pretty awsome, so I'm up for more of that naturally as well, sort of the icing.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />1010011010 - Binary of the Beast!</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
