        <tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><a name="45493"></a><span class="name"><span class="usercolor">Loriwen</span></span><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_offline.gif" border="0" align="absbottom" alt="Offline" title="Offline" /><div class="gensmall"><img src="images/ranks/rank_5.gif" alt="Beguiler" title="Beguiler" border="0" /><br />Beguiler</div><div align="center"><img src="images/avatars/14321674104001c1decd155.jpg" alt="Avatar" border="0" /></div><br /><div align="left" class="gensmall">Joined:&nbsp;25 Sep 2003</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Total posts:&nbsp;131</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Location:&nbsp;Norrath</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Gender:&nbsp;Female</div></td>
                <td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=45493#45493"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu May 27, 2004 10:56 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=45493"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Warning, long post ahead:
<br />

<br />
The movies didn't have time to go into the detail that books did, nor did they touch on much from the other books and tales that Tolkien wrote.  Even reading the trilogy isn't enough to get the full story, as other sources, mainly The Silmarillion, provide more details.  So, for someone who has only seen the movies, the full story will never really be understood, only guesses based upon the information provided.  
<br />

<br />
This is fine.  As a trilogy of movies, the LoTR series stands on its own.  It was made to be a faithful adaptation, so that the legions of Tolkien fans would still appreciate it, but it was altered to be a movie that the uninitiated could enjoy, as well.  In doing so, things were left out or never fully explained, and if you really want to know, you will need to read the source material for yourself.  Even today, decades later, some of it is still debated over what certain things truly mean.  I'll put down some info here, to at least give you what I know of some of the things you refer to.
<br />

<br />
Here's a very bried rundown of Middle-Earth's (hereafter just ME) history.
<br />

<br />
There is God, also called Eru or Iluvatar who dwelt in the Timeless Halls.  He created the Ainur, or Holy Ones of which there were two divisions, the Valar and the Maiar.  The Valar are like lesser gods, and the Maiar are their servants.  The Ainur sang before Eru and received a vision of the world, Arda.  He was pleased and sent those that would go into the world to create in real what had been just vision and song.  Thus, the world was made.
<br />

<br />
During that song, Melkor, greatest of the Valar, felt that he could wave his own imaginings into the song, thus creating things of himself and not in accord with Iluvatar.  Note, however, that each time he sang in discord, Iluvatar revealed a new part of the song that made the harmony whole again.  After doing this a couple of times, he ended the song and said something like, "Know that there is nothing that does not have its source in me, nor can alter the music of his own despite, but in doing so prove but mine instrument in the devising of things even more wonderful than he imagined."  So, despite Melkor's attempts, all things are of Iluvatar and will, in the end, serve him.
<br />

<br />
Okay, so some of the Ainur, including Melkor, went into Arda and created the world that they had sung about.  The Valar, and the Maiar with them, dwelt in the West of Arda in a place called Valinor.  Melkor proved to be their enemy and eventually chose ME as his stomping grounds from which to wreak havoc on the world. The Valar made two lamps (great big huge towers with light to light the world) and Melkor knocked 'em down.  The light was then captured in two trees in Valinor.  Eventually, he along with Shelob's mom, destroyed the trees, too, and the remaining light was turned into the Sun and the Moon.  At some point during this, the first children of Iluvatar arose in the world, the Elves.  Unfortunately, the awoke in ME and Melkor decided to hate them.  So, the Valar eventually made contact with the elves and invited them to come live in Valinor.  Some did, some didn't, and some tried to make the trip, but stopped along the way and thus, you have the different branches of the Elves.    
<br />

<br />
A whole lot of stuff happened and to try to go into detail would take a long time.  Just know that there's a buch of history here that I'm glossing over.  An elf, Feanor, living in Valinor, made the Silmarils, which contained some of the light of the glorious Trees before they were destroyed.  A lot of bad stuff happened because of this, and Feanor's arrogance, and Melkor's influence, and eventually some of the High Elves (those that lived in Valinor) went back into ME.  There, a whole lot more stuff happened, including the appearance of Man, eventually leading to Melkor's downfall, from whence he was thrust into the Timeless void and his only influence upon ME after that was in the darkness he had implanted in the minds and hearts of Elves and Man, or in the activities of this servants that remained.
<br />

<br />
Morgoth had many of the Maiar that followed him when he "rebelled" and became an evil jerk.  Of them were Sauron, the Balrogs, the Dragons, and a whole host of other nasties.  Whatever their original form or purpose, they became nasty evil things in his service.  After his death, Sauron pleaded forgiveness of the Valar and then, of course, became a bad guy in his own right.  
<br />

<br />
Eventually, the greatest of Men came to dwell on the island of Numenor.  The Numenoreans were blessed with long life and dwelt within sight of the West, but weren't allowed to go there.  You see, Man's gift from Eru, is death.  Now, it's not so bad a thing as you might think.  The Elves are tied to the world, even when they die, their spirits go to Valinor and dwell in some sort of spirit place.  Only Man is given the gift of true death and, thus, leaves Arda for places even the Valar haven't been told of.  Melkor had used this uncertainty, though, to place a fear of death in Man's heart.  Sauron battled with the Numenoreans, but sensing their army would defeat his and he'd have to start building all over again, he instead surrendered and was taken prisoner to Numenor.  Where he, of course, whispered and connived and playing upon Man's fear of death, eventually caused the Numenoreans to seek to sail to Valinor and take it by force if necessary so they could be immortal, too.  Iluvatar acted and sunk Numenor into the ocean, and then removed Valinor from the world, making the world round so that any who sailed to the west would only find they'd circled the world and ended up back where they started.  Only the Elves were allowed to sail the "Straight Path" and go into the west ... well, and some chosen few that went with them.
<br />

<br />
Alright, so during his time in ME, Sauron created rings of power.  He was gonna use them to corrupt and control everything, because he'd secretly made the one ring to control them all.  The elves sensed this and thus were not taken in by it, their rings remained mostly pure.  The dwarves were not easily corruptible and it only really made them kind of greedy and distrustful.  Man, on the other hand, was all sorts of easy to corrupt and thus the nine kings with the nine rings became the Nazgul (or Ulairi, aka the Ring-wraiths.)  Then the great battle happened, when Elves and Men worked together and they managed to defeat Sauron and you know what followed from the movies.  Then, time passed.
<br />

<br />
However, as you know, Sauron was not destroyed, so eventually he came back.  First as just a shadow of his former power, hinted at in the Hobbit.  He was the Necromancer who lived in Dol Guldur in Mirkwood.  Then, the nine went to Mordor and prepared his place there and he went back to his kingdom, restored as much of his power as he could, and then started looking to get the ring.
<br />

<br />
As the first hint of Sauron appeared during this time, the Istari came into Middle-Earth from the west.  Gandalf is one of the Istari, or wizards.  Wizards in Middle-Earth were not just a class like in DnD or EQ.  ME is filled with people, places and things that have multiple names, due to the different races and languages.  Wizard is simply the name Men used to refer to the Istari.  There were five, but only three were named.  The elves called them Mithrandir, Curunir and Radagast.  Men called them Gandalf, Saruman, and ... uh, well Radagast, cause he didn't play much of a role.  Anyway, here's a quote from the appendix.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">When maybe a thousand years had passed, and the first shadow had fallen on Greenwood the Great, the Istari or Wizards appeared in Middle-earth. It was afterwards said that they came out of the far West and were messengers sent to contest the power of Sauron, and to unite all those who had the will to resist him; but they were forbidden to match his power with power, or to seek to dominate Elves or Men by force and fear. 
<br />
They came therefore in the shape of Men, though they were never young and aged only slowly, and they had many powers of mind and hand. They revealed their true names to few,' but used such names as were given to them. The two highest of this order (of whom it is said there were five) were called by the Eldar Curunír, 'the Man of Skill', and Mithrandir, 'the Grey Pilgrim', but by Men in the North Saruman and Gandalf. Curunír journeyed often into the East, but dwelt at last in Isengard. Mithrandir was closest in friendship with the Eldar, and wandered mostly in the West and never made for himself any lasting abode.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Only Cirdan, who kept the Havens where Elves sailed to the West, knew what they actually were.  He only told Galadriel and Elrond.  Gandalf also at one point says, when discussing his names, "Olorin I was in my youth that was forgotten."  In the Silmarillion, when the Maiar are being spoken of, it is stated, "Wisest of the Maiar was Olorin.  He too dwelt in Lorien, but his ways took him often to the house of Nienna, and of her he learned pity and paitence."  Thus, Gandalf (and the rest of the Istari) are revealed to be of the Maiar, but have taken on mortal form in ME.
<br />

<br />
Saruman was the most skilled of the Istari, but he, in studying the rings of power, eventually was seduced by Sauron and you know the results of that, for the most part.  Gandalf stayed true and did what he was meant to do, which was simply help, with wisdom and advice, lead others to stand against Sauron.  He only really entered battle himself when no other options were available, and that is why he fought the Balrog.  Otherwise, it would have killed the entire Fellowship.
<br />

<br />
Now, the Istari were given (or took) mortal bodies while in ME, so in the battle with the Balrog, Gandalf was killed also.  However, Iluvatar sent him back to continue with his task until it was done.  So, when he was sent back, he was more powerful.  The title of "the White" was originally Saruman's as he was the most powerful of the Istari, but Gandalf took that title as he came back the most powerful and Saruman had already fallen to Sauron.
<br />

<br />
The Balrog, or Valaraukar, were spirits of fire of the Maiar, fallen into Melkor's service.  Gandalf was rightfully afraid to face the Balrog, for while he was given a mortal body, the Balrog was in it's true form.  (Well, all the Ainur that came to Arda took on bodies of some sort, so even those aren't their "true" form, but that's being nitpicky.)  However, Gandalf did win, even in dying, and thus defeated one of the last ancient scourges of Melkor.  Then, Eru sent him back to help deal with Sauron.
<br />

<br />
One should note here, that while there are power levels amonst the Ainur, the Valar and Maiar, and that Elves seem to be more powerful than Man, in the tales these differences aren't always so great that lesser beings can't rise against the greater ones.  In the Silmarillion, both elf and man contest with Melkor and his servants directly and some even win.  So, the idea of Gandalf even in mortal form, besting the Balrog is not a stretch.  So, it should also be known that a mortal (a Black Numenorean lord, so greater than a regular man), turned ring-wraith, and especially the greatest of the Nazgul bearing a ring of power and linked directly to Sauron (the most powerful of the Maiar), would have the power to battle with Gandalf, even as Gandalf the White.  The outcome was never certain, and when Gandalf learned of Denethor's insanity which would lead to Faramir's doom, he had to choose.  In the end, I think it was his nature as an advisor that led him to choose to save the life of Faramir rather than contest the might of the Witch-king.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, here's some info on the Witch-King from the Wikipedia website:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The Witch-king was originally a Black Númenórean lord. In the Second Age, he was given one of nine Rings of Power to help rule over his realm. He and eight others were ensnared by Sauron, who made them the Nazgûl. He became the lord of the Wraiths, and Sauron's chief servant. He later founded the realm of Angmar, destroyed the kingdoms of Arnor, and then besieged and took Minas Ithil, renaming it Minas Morgul, and became its lord. Eärnur, King of Gondor, who had previously routed the Witch-king from Arnor at the Battle of Fornost but was unable to slay him (at which point the Noldorin Elf-lord Glorfindel prophesied to Eärnur that no man would slay the Witch-king), accepted the Witch-king's challenge (against the advice of the prophecy of Glorfindel) to meet him in single combat in Minas Morgul, and never returned. From that day until the coronation of Elessar hundreds of years later, Gondor was ruled by a Steward, as there was none to claim the kingship. 
<br />

<br />
He led the search for the One Ring, and later Mordor's assault on Minas Tirith. Here he was slain by Théoden's niece Éowyn with the aid of the hobbit Meriadoc Brandybuck, thereby fulfilling the prophecy that no man should slay him. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
In the end, and I need to end this as I've gone on for some time, it really boils down to the differences that always happen between book and movie.  The movies didn't, and couldn't really even in the 9 hour time frame, explain all of this.  If they had, they probably would have lost or annoyed a good portion of the audience.  So, the story was "Hollywood-ized" and parts were changed or just left unmentioned.  Yes, movie did play up the confrontation, and then never really got across the reasons why it didn't happen.  I've also heard from many fans, and I agree, that the scene between Eowyn and the Witch-king just didn't play out well, but we've had years to imagine it in our heads.
<br />

<br />
I'll end this by saying that anyone who really enjoyed the movies, but always felt there was more and they really wanted to know about, should read the books.  All of them.  The Hobbit, the trilogy, the Silmarillion and the other myriad shorter tales that comprise Tolkien's work.  The man created a world and even then, he never got to finish it.  There is so much rich material here that today's writers, and even those who create game worlds for RPG's, pale by comparison.  And it all started because a little kid named John Ronald Reuel Tolkien like to make up play languages.
<br />

<br />
ps.  I'll also add something I read once and found rather interesting and amusing.  The entire story of the Hobbit is a special forces first-strike attack instigated by Gandalf.  Knowing that Sauron was returning, Gandalf puts together a team of dwarves and one hobbit and sets them on the trail of Smaug.  Smaug, as one of the fallen Maiar, would have been a powerful "unit" of Sauron once the dark lord returned to power.  So, Gandalf used his team to take out that unit before it ever had a chance to come into play.  Wily old bastard.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: violet">Sage Loriwen Tathrenlin</span></span>
<br />
