                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I love this theory, but I am not sure its factual. I don't think JRR Tolkien thought all this out when he wrote "The Hobbit" But it sounds good.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
He didn't.  But it -is- his official retroactive justification. <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Similarly, he didn't think about the ring being The Ring in The Hobbit either, and in fact had to go back and edit the Riddles in the Dark chapter in an effort to make it more consistant with LotR.
<br />

<br />
With regard to the unraised question that Isevan sortof seems to have, namely "Could Gandalf defeat the Witch King?" the answer is "No one knows."  Certainly Gandalf falls into the category of "no man", as he is a Maiar spirit (An 'angel of sorts) given flesh, but just because you're not a man doesn't give you immediate license to kill the Witch King, who was, after all, the mightiest of the Ring Wraiths, and a sorceror (not be confused with Wizard) of no small ability. 
<br />

<br />
In the extended cut of Fellowship, Gandalf says "There are many powers in this world, Frodo Baggins, for good or for evil. Some are greater than I am."  That's pretty close to verbatim from the book, but it's incomplete - the full quote continues to add, "And against some I have not yet been tested." - conclusion: Gandalf himself doesn't know if he can defeat the Witch King.  He certainly INTENDS to challenge him, since he can't think of anyone else who can do it, since there is something of a shortage of battleworthy non-"men" in Minas Tirith at that point.  However, when he would have been out challenging the Witch King on the battlefield, Gandalf is "distracted" by the need to rescue Faramir (in the book, he says something to the effect of "I will come, because there is no other help that can reach him, but great evil will come of this.") and as such, Eowyn and Merry face the Witch King instead. 
<br />

<br />
For those of you who are perhaps not interested in reading the books (for whatever unfathomable reasons you might have <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" /> ) but are still curious about a lot of this stuff, I can recommend a couple of good resources.  Firstly, there is <a href="http://www.theonering.net" target="_blank" class="postlink">The One Ring.Net</a> which was/is a site for all things related to the movies (Originally it was sortof a 'spy report' site, but it's grown a lot since then) and more particularly the <a href="http://greenbooks.theonering.net/index.shtml" target="_blank" class="postlink">Green Books</a> section, which contains, amoung other things, an excellent Q&A archive on all manner of things - including several about the whole Witch-King prophecy.
<br />

<br />
Another site worth checking out, probably for the more advanced Middle-Earth junkie, is <a href="http://www.glyphweb.com/arda/" target="_blank" class="postlink">The Encyclopedia of Arda</a> a monumental cross linked encyclopedia of just about everything in Middle Earth.   Worth a stroll for both the veteran who wants to know what the deal was with <a href="http://www.glyphweb.com/arda/e/elrond.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Elrond's Parentage</a> complete with family tree, or the ravening Fangirl hungry for any scrap of information about <a href="http://www.glyphweb.com/arda/l/legolas.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Legolas</a> - it's a fine way to answer your questions.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
