                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Chagrin, I'm assuming you've only seen the movies and are basing all your expectations from them.  While I think Peter Jackson did a wonderful job of realizing Tolkien's work, there are some problems with his translation that leave questions like this in the air.  I can't really answer based on what Jackson was thinking or trying to envision, because it does seem as if he were building up toward a cinematic confrontation which let down a lot of people who don't know the real story.
<br />

<br />
I can give you a very basic run-down, though.  There was a battle once in Middle-Earth where the Maiar did match their power against the might of Morgoth (Sauron's Master) and in doing so, the entire area of Beleriand (a huge area of several nations) was broken and destroyed, with small parts remaining that eventually became Lindon.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">This 'war of the gods' left Beleriand devastated: '...so great was the fury of those adversaries that the northern regions of the western world were rent asunder, and the sea roared in through many chasms...' (Quenta Silmarillion 24).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
A lot of time passed and many other things happened.
<br />

<br />
Eventually, the Istari (wizards, Gandalf, Saruman, et al) were sent into Middle-Earth to contest Sauron and his bid to dominate all.  However, they were forbidden to match "power with power" against the Dark Lord.  It was feared that if such a battle happened again, the same fate would befall this area as it did on Beleriand.  Their only job was to guide and counsel others.
<br />

<br />
As for magic, that is an entire other topic that would take way too long to discuss.  Suffice to say, Gandalf was not a D&D wizard and shouldn't be expected to act like one.  In simplest terms, the closest description I could give is that he was an angel cloaked in a slow-aging mortal body and given strict rules as to what he could and could not do.  Yes, Gandalf is a badass, and if the gloves were off, a match for just about any of the dark forces except Sauron himself.
<br />

<br />
A few questions, Goloth ...
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">First, Morgoth did not bring the dragons. He had corrupted great eagles into forms now known as dragons.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Not sure where you're getting that info, please let me know because that's the first I've heard of it.  I find nothing in the Silmarillion on it, nor on Tolkien web sites.  <a href="http://www.glyphweb.com/arda/default.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">The Encyclopedia of Arda</a> states simply:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Mighty reptilian creatures who ranked among the most feared of the servants of the Dark Lord. <span style="font-weight: bold">Of the origins of dragons, no tale tells</span>; the first of them to be seen was Glaurung, Father of Dragons, who first issued from Angband in the middle of the First Age. After Glaurung came many others to strike fear into Elves and Men for the next three ages; among them were Ancalagon the first winged dragon, Scatha who dwelt in the cold northern wastes, and Smaug, last of the great dragons.
<br />

<br />
Dragons have powers of intelligence and speech, and many are also able to cast the dragon-spell, a bewildering confusion that affects any who gaze into the eye of the creature.
<br />

<br />
The dragons were not destroyed at the end of the Third Age; some are said to have survived to our own time, but the great worms and drakes of the Elder Days are no more.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Is it in one of the letters or other tales?
<br />

<br />
Also, I can't find where trolls were implicitly stated to have been made from Ents.  The only Tolkien reference I've found just says, they were made 'in mockery of the Ents'.
<br />

<br />
As for Gandalf and the other Istari .. again, I'd be interested in knowing where you get your information from.  Gandalf acknowledged that Saruman was the Chief of the order, and the eldest of them, as well.  Other than that, no real ranking was given that I could find.  Also, Saruman is the only one that we're told grew to lust for power.  Radagast became interested in living things, animals mostly, and neglected his mission.  He only ever aided Saruman out of ignorance, though.  As for the other two, Alantar and Pallando, not much is known aside that they were dressed in blue and went further east and left all knowledge of the tales.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Tolkien tells us 'What success they [Alatar and Pallando] had I do not know; but I fear they failed, as Saruman did, though doubtless in different ways; and I suspect they were the founders or beginners of secret cults and 'magic' traditions that outlasted the fall of Sauron.' (The Letters of J.R.R. Tolkien, No. 211).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Anyway, what it boils down to for me is this ... if anyone wants to really know answers, they should read Tolkien's work for themselves.  At the very least, the LotR books, but also The Hobbit and the Silmarillion.  If really interested, there are a dozen or more other books, mostly collections of Tolkien's other writings of ME and letters to friends, family, and peers, but those are mostly for the hard-core fan.
<br />

<br />
However, if reading this much isn't for you, most of your answers can be found at the Enclyclopedia of Arda linked above or <a href="http://greenbooks.theonering.net/" target="_blank" class="postlink">The Green Books</a>.  Both of these are wonderful sites.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: violet">Sage Loriwen Tathrenlin</span></span>
<br />
Coercer of <a href="http://www.invictvs.com/index.asp" target="_blank" class="postlink">Invictvs</a> on Tholuxe Paells
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=370372" target="_blank" class="postlink">Magelo</a> | <a href="http://members.aol.com/loriweneq/myhomepage/loriwenfile.jpg" target="_blank" class="postlink">File Card</a>
